description: From Middle English stench, from Old English stenċ (“stench, odor, fragrance”), from Proto-Germanic *stankwiz (“smell, fragrance, odor”), from Proto-Indo-European *stengʷ- (“to push, thrust”). Cognate with Dutch stank (“stench, odor”), German Stank, Gestank (“stench, odor, smell”), Danish stank (“stench”), Swedish stank (“stench”), Icelandic stækja (“stench”).

entries.meaning: a strong foul smell; a stink.
(obsolete) A smell or odour, not necessarily bad.

verbs.description: stench (third-person singular simple present stenches, present participle stenching, simple past and past participle stenched)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To cause to emit a disagreeable odour; to cause to stink.
